share_exp: The amount of time we’ve had to put into remediation and babysitting contractors is burning us out. My husband has taken off over 4 weeks of work just to help us return to our home 4 1/2 mos post fire. It dominates every minute of our life and we’re part of a large group of people who are largely silent in our recovery. It’s just not about being able to feel joy but having a spare moment to not be at the house working. Its about painful amounts of paperwork for insurance reimbursements. It’s about getting a good nights sleep. It’s about wanting to know our home is safe to live in again. It’s about missing our neighbors and friends. It’s hard to be a community when all of our friends are spread out into 8 different towns, all just trying to get their own heads above water. And the world moves on. Not clinically depressed but exhausted and sometimes just mad

name: Bruce & Marylee Janda
share_exp: As difficult and stressful as this tragedy has been, and I still feel it night and day, the stress has been exacerbated ten-fold by having to deal with our insurance company, State Farm. The toll that is taken daily while working on our own or with our adjuster on issues of coverage, debris removal, and especially the trauma and PTSD of having to list every item that we can possibly remember that was lost in the fire is immense and exhausting. Finding a long-term rental was incredibly exhausting. Finding a replacement car was exhausting and expensive. Interviewing, vetting and choosing a builder is exhausting. Trying to decipher the SBA disaster loan process is exhausting. Deciding who to have perform debris removal is exhausting. Chasing after replacement stuff, free or otherwise, is exhausting. Attending multiple fire-related meetings weekly is exhausting, even the ones where we can reconnect with neighbors, although these are deeply gratifying as well. The last four and a half months have been overwhelming. My husband and I are really really tired. We’re still not sleeping well. We don’t have any energy or interest in cooking and so are not eating well. We are triggered by wind and the smell of smoke. Everywhere I go, I look for signs of fire or how to avoid fire or what whatever place I’m looking at might look like after a fire. I pack and re-pack a go bag and wake up at night worrying about having to evacuate and start our lives over yet again. I worry that our old dog (thank goodness she evacuated with us) won’t make it back home, that her last day on Mulberry St was evacuation day, because it’s going to take so long to rebuild, and, boy, does that make me sad.

fire_impacts_13_text: I lost a contract on a home in Original Town Superior that was under contract at 101 Coal Creek where I planned to develop affordable housing.  I also lost the opportunity to buy out my partner on a vacant lot at 102 Maple St Superior due to the economic impacts from the fire and a lack of interest by banks to underwrite a loan to develop affordable net zero wildfire resilient housing.
evac_prompt_18_text: State Trooper drove through my court announcing evacuation due to risk of fire.
reminders_9_text: My small business was directly impacted by the Marshall Fire. My small business applied for a US SBA Disaster Recovery Loan but was denied even though the US SBA Regional Manager at the Disaster Recovery Center told me and read directly from the Standard Operations Manual that my business was ELIGIBLE for a Disaster Loan. I have appealed the US SBA decision, requested help from Congressman Neguse, Senator Bennet, Boulder County Commissioners, Boulder County Community Foundation Wildfire Fund,  Town of Superior, City of Louisville to support my efforts to secure a disaster recovery loan to build wildfire resilient, net zero energy affordable housing for those who lost homes.  My small business presented to the Town of Superior City Council on October 11, 2021 to collaborate with the Town to develop affordable housing but was denied a collaborative public/private partnership. To date I have not received a penny of assistance from the US SBA even though I was impacted and was willing to do all of the planning and development due diligence for developing the net zero energy wildfire resilient affordable and workforce housing.
ncarfire_6_text: One of my business clients lives in an areas surrounded by the City of Boulder Open Space and therefore at risk.  I drove to their home to assist with their perimeter fire prevention system in case it was needed. Thankfully the wind was blowing to the South.

heal: I came down with a respiratory infection that lasted one one in January/February. I recovered in about 35 days. My dog also came down with a respiratory infection but has not recovered and in his last X-ray showed continued infection in his lungs.  He is on two medications for the past two months but only slightly improving. He also has an enlarged heart.
religion_8_text: Spiritual following American Indian tradition for respect of Mother Earth. Brought up strong Catholic in Chicago Illinois so I attend non-denominational church on occasion.

I also firmly believe the best way we can improve life on this planet for all species is advance knowledge with the younger generation by creating on the job training opportunities/internships that will give the youth of our world first hand experiences on understanding economic, environmental, social problems and participating first hand in creating solutions to these inter-generational challenges.

share_exp: I lived in this area over 40 years.  Every winter everything drys out and we have days of over 50 mph winds.We were luckly this happen during the day with only 3 loss of life, it would been different at night.  There was no way to fight the 100 mph fire. There will be a next time, I just very surprised it hasn't happened before.  I heard first hand that a woman was seen in Marshall lighting these fires and then I find out there were several arsonist that were caught and then turned loose weeks before the Marshall fire.  I hope this is not true, but if true, this go soft on crime has to stop.  I will make sure I don't use mulch ever again in my yard, I will have a 5 foot no burn around my home with no plants or anything else near my house to lead fire to it.  I was the change in wind direction that allowed the fire fighters to save my house and my neighbors.   I may not be so lucky next time.  I feel that the city of Louisville did nothing to warn me of the fire.   We have sirens and yet none were used.

heal: We have lived in Boulder since the Marshall Fire as our home is at a fire line and has needed significant remediation/restoration. We wore N95 masks for the first weeks following the fire when going to our neighborhood/home. Often had stomach aches after visiting our home; unclear if that was due to physiological factors or psychological ones (every home behind ours burned and is VERY visible from all back windows; all of our belongings haphazardly removed from our home). After a month following air scrubbers running in our home and popcorn ceiling and carpet removed, and home cleaned, we stopped wearing them. Since our ceilings were re-rolled, my mouth and tongue burn each time I go into our home.
stress_symptoms_5_text: Stomach aches when visiting home for first few months.
share_exp: '-Emergency response system failed miserably and needs to be reviewed and improved. If the fire had occurred at night, MANY would have died. We were communicating w neighbors and pulling up news sites to see why so much smoke and determine how close. We left because a neighbor texted that they saw the fire in the field just up from our home and emergency vehicles finally came though our neighborhood saying to evacuate immediately. I didn't receive a notification on my phone until nearly an hour later. When evacuating, it took an hour to go 1 mile through downtown Louisville. -Information is badly needed for those whose homes didn't burn as they have been much ignored to focus on those who lost homes. Homes at the fire lines like ours that are immediately adjacent MANY burned homes (toxins!) have been given little direction on how to safely remediate homes and yards. We have no idea if our home/yard will be safe for our family following remediation (will we be facing cancer in the future as a result?), as the remediation/restoration process was poorly informed, chaotic, with most remediation/restoration companies overwhelmed and doing a poor job. -The day this survey arrived, I was thinking how much we need better information following fires (these aren't the first urban fires!!) and researchers to gather data about physical and mental health throughout the process and for years following. We have no idea if the steps we have taken will make our home and neighborhood safe enough to live in.

share_exp: The Marshall Fire was one of three fires reported in Boulder County on December 30th 2021. It burned through downtown Superior and crossed I36 to burn into Louisville and unicorporated Boulder County along Davidson Mesa. There was inadequate water pressure to allow responding friefighters to fight the numerous structure fires they encountered. There was a totally inadequate early warning system and alerts didn't happen for many residents. The result was total devastation and it will be many years before residences are rebuilt. In the mean time many fire affected rresidents are totally displaced and unable to live in and around Superior and Louisville due to inadequate housing and rental properties. This survey doesn't even begin to capture the complexities and stress that those of us who are displaced by the fire have experienced and continue to experience. The response of Boulder County has added to our stress due to poor communication and inadequate planning and response.

air_cleaning_4_text: Honestly we can't afford to have someone clean our house since we did not meet our insurance deductible. So, we were about 5k in sunk costs while evacuated.
heal: If this is related to something that Boulder County is not releasing about the toxicity in burn areas as it relates to the immediate burn sites, I will be extremely annoyed and frustrated at another miss at transparency from the state, county and town. Today I have my windows open for fresh air but will be closing directly after wrapping this up.
share_exp: . I can't imagine what we've been breathing outside over the last few months. Also, we did not meet our deductible to help with any major cleaning of the house and although were somewhat compensated from FEMA for new clothes, food expenses, etc. it was less than half of what we had to spend while evacuated. We've now started this year at a financial loss because of something that was outside of our control. Inflation is not helping to balance out our financial picture and so we are essentially limping along after having major loss at the beginning of the year. Meaning no camps for kids, a limited budget to work with and just overall a struggle, I know we didn't lose out house and I'm so grateful that we don't have to jump through the hoops of rebuilding. However, this other part of the picture of people who still have their homes but were not able to afford to have a professional come in to clean, and therefore may be leading to serious health concerns down the road has never been discussed. I'm not even going to start about the piss poor communication the day of the fire. I was lucky to get out of here with my animals, but as I stated had to have my husband in Denver call me to evacuate. No sirens, no texts, no emails.  And as I was evacuating I got stuck in the traffic circle in the front of our neighborhood in complete smoke and ash for about ten minutes. I thought my life was going to end there. A lot is wrong. I'm happy to be part of the solution, but until the conversation becomes real about the fallout of this catastrophe I'm happy to just try to keep myself and my family as safe as I can while living in this area. Which honestly doesn't feel like it's worth it anymore.

share_exp: Suggestion: I could not “unselect” once I answered a question. Future surveys should allow one to unselect if a person changes her mind. I sometimes disagree with the methods government uses to control resource usage. For example there is a penalty for putting in over a certain number of water taps (sinks, showers, etc). # of taps may suggest more water usage but that is not a certainty. Instead, they should actual tax water usage over a certain amount. Monitoring water usage is accurate, restricting taps is not accurate and is exactly the kind of government policy that irritates people. Many in my neighborhood are very irritated by this tap policy.

share_exp: We have felt that so many people in the community and elsewhere unaffected by the fire have been so gracious and kind and wanting to help. We’ve also seen in some ways others that were affected by the fire that are somewhat entitled and not that thankful. Examples of folks getting $100k in godundme funds and then buy a third home while waiting for the rebuild because they just can’t think about renting. So thankful that the attention this disaster has gotten has helped the community so much and I hope that others in other situations where they wouldn’t receive funds from wealthy friends and colleagues can get similar assistance. And that we all affected by this event pay it forward when we are in a good situation and others are in need.

share_exp: My stress comes from insurance company and remediation company being sneaky and with holding funds.  We have the insurance funds to rebuild and replace yard and trees, but stress comes when remembering they are going to nickel and dime you and payout as little as possible and tell you you have to wear your clothing and use your electronics, whereas industrial Hygenist says you can never truly ‘clean’ clothing, soft goods, electronics -will still have soot ash char from urban fire (our windows broken, entire neighborhood burned to describe proximity) fire footprint does not stop at property line.  It insurance company would just pay out limits, I could relax and move forward with purchasing new hairdryer, toaster, vacuum, etc etc etc getting yard replaced now (but insurance is telling me everything is ‘fine’). Remediation company has already ‘cleaned’ and stored everything, hearing I could have chosen what to clean and received funds of what it costs to clean (then used that to replace the minimum essentials).  Don’t know of any place affordable to accurately test fabrics food and electronics for toxins that have imbedded themselves.  Thank you.

share_exp: The Marshall Fire was the most unexpected and traumatic event I've ever experienced.  I'm very grateful that my husband, dog and I were able to evacuate safely and had friends that sheltered and fed us until we could find our own housing.  I'm also very thankful that the entire Boulder County community was so responsive and provided so much that we needed.  People have been extremely generous and wonderful.

heal: Inner ear issues. Inability to sleep. Mental trauma.
share_exp: The local, county, state, and federal governments and officials are derelict in their duties. I honestly do not understand where my taxes go. My community was living under a false sense of security. For deity of choice sake, I lived across from the police department and half a block from the fire department, yet nobody could alert me that there was fire in the area? Disgraceful. Another thing that is disgraceful is monies collected to help fire victims are being spent on full on bullshit! How many entities are putting their hands out to get a cut? Why are government officials allowing this to happen? You all ought to be ashamed of yourselves. Furthermore, this open space so-called management in Boulder County is laughable.  This ought to serve as a gut check for you all as you are entrusted to public safety, yet you failed and continue to fail, and continue to accept a paycheck. Really? Can you look at yourselves in the mirror? If you can, you are not human.

stress_symptoms_5_text: mild panic attacks, surges in anger, inability to pivot/cope when things change
share_exp: I know that for research purposes you have to obtain quantifiable responses, but I would have liked having an opportunity to expand on some of my answers. Specifically, with regard to rebuilding, we will not nearly be settled or even close to finished with rebuilding a year from now, and neither will most of our neighbors. We expect to be displaced through the end of 2023 if not into early 2024.  Briefly, though, I will say that I never imagined something like this really happening -- a wildfire is something that happens elsewhere to other people. Looking back at my mental state, I realize that I was in complete shock in January and into February. I have few memories of that time and it feels unreal, dreamlike. I am only now, and slowly, recovering my resilience and ability to manage things going wrong. Like, if I make the wrong turn when driving, I can end up furious and screaming or in tears. I kind of wish I'd had the opportunity to do this survey in March for the first time.

share_exp: Due to the lack of evacuation notice, there was only a police car at 2 not letting us turn left on Dillon when an hour before we were supposed to be evacuated. And based on my talks with neighbors maybe half of us did not receive an evacuation notice, we even had a landline, but no speakers of any sort were in our neighborhood of Coal Creek Ranch-South. Police and firemen did not come to save people until after numerous houses were on fire on Troon Court and Turnberry. Some left with their houses on fire.  And have met others in other neighborhoods that also left with their houses on fire. And lack of communication from the county and city to us and the news stations, I left my cats behind and everything else, not knowing the little grass fire at Avista just before 2 was the same fire behind Target and Costco.  Which even then nothing was known about the first neighborhood to go, Sagamore.  The news stations didn't even know hundreds of homes were already gone by 3, ours looked to be about 4-4:30, and 9News in particular thought just one house on Marshall Road because they could see it from the Louisville side, looked like maybe they were in the cinema parking lot.

Talking about police or fire reminds me how they drove through our neighborhood NOT WARNING ANYONE but somehow new criminal laws are a good thing(?). share_exp: We were not notified at all of the fire even though it came within a half mile of our home. We were shocked to learn that we either had to have a land line sign-up to be notified (we have since signed-up). That is a HUGE problem. Louisville seems like a fairly progressive and thoughtful community and making people signup for an alert seems incredibly short-sighted. Some of our tax money could be diverted from non-essential areas to create a solution to this problem. This is ridiculously wrong. There should be a way to gather phone numbers from our public service or water bills to feed into a main database that can automatically dispense a message to all residents of Louisville. THIS NEEDS TO BE FIXED.

share_exp: Have lived in Boulder, Louisville and now Superior for almost a lifetime.  This fire was a perfect storm of many conditions and events occurring at the same time to make the fire destruction a 100 year or 500 year storm event.  Winds of 90 mph plus, humans and considerable dryness came together and the results can be seen every day as people venture from their homes.  Hopefully we all can move forward to help or prevent this from happening again under listed conditions.  Just if this event was to happen in the middle of the night what could of happened.  We feel lucky, blessed that our houses were spared but feel badly for folks  months after this catastrophe.

name: Lisa & Aaron Clauset
stress_symptoms_5_text: Burnout from dealing with recovery efforts
share_exp: For me, the most traumatic part of the event was the recovery. Our insurance provider was generally helpful, but their recommended vendors for different aspects of the recovery effort were nightmarish. These companies are a total scam. They are incompetent, poorly managed, don't do the work they are supposed to, claim to do work the didn't do, lie repeatedly, damage the home, and bill the insurance for as much work as they can. I spent more than 100 hours (outside of my job) managing these incompetent contractors, leading to severe emotional stress and burnout trying to keep my job and manage the recovery process. On top of that, we were displaced from our home for several weeks during some of the recovery work, and no one could give me straight, evidence-based answers about the actual risks associated with the ash etc. from the fire. Different contracts said wildly different things, making it extremely difficult to make informed decisions for myself and my family.

Also, I helped coordinate the Chrysalis Initiative, which is Christ the Servant Lutheran Church's response to help survivors of the Marshall Fire.  Many of our members lost homes or were displaced for a long period of time.  In this role, I have spent a lot of time supporting fire survivors and this experience impacted my answers in this survey.  For more information about the Chrysalis Initiative, you can go to the CTS website.

I never got an evacuation order but had always told my husband that we leave if there’s a warning. I had family effected by fire a few years ago.  2. I turned off my “do not disturb” feature (which I used to silence calls/texts at night) so that I could receive emergency notifications while sleeping.   3. share_exp: It is difficult not to feel ambivalent about many issues that arise out of this disaster.  I sure don't know everything, but I feel lucky that I still have a home.  My personal challenges in responding to the Marshall Fire have been compounded having family that lost their home, and by a professional role in which I have had major responsibility to secure resources to help families and community agencies impacted by the fire.  I have heard many difficult things, every day, for months.  But I am overcome with admiration for first responders, City officials and staff, and volunteers who took on the most difficult roles, sometimes even as their own homes were lost.  I have been deeply touched by the businesses that have dug deep to help out.  Louisville has been courageous, and for the most part, we have stuck together.  There is comfort in that.

share_exp: Personally, I'm very glad that my family escaped the evacuation process (because we happened to be out of town, up in the mountains), but it was also stressful being out of town. We had two dogs in the house and thankfully, were able to coordinate their evacuation (along with the removal of some of our most important documents and back-up hard drive) with our retired neighbors across the street. The fire emphasized to me the importance of knowing your neighbors - which seems simple, but in this day, it's not always a given. Neighbors helped check that others were evacuating (since we didn't receive any alert), gave updates throughout the day from their security cameras (if they were still operating) and coordinated with each other to help get the gas turned back on, so that we could return to our homes.

heal: Sore throat dry smoky air; issues re no home heat for 10 days (stressful but not major); stress re no power, no heat, sometimes no land line; being alone with all this and CONCERNED EVERY TIME WE HAVE HIGH WIND.  Depressed if this constant concern will be permanent; sometimes hard to sleep.
share_exp: Wish that I had been contacted somehow late on Dec. 30.  No phone messages got through to me.  Electric/gas/internet/phone went down.  Saw and smelled lots of smoke.  Messages were sent (I got them much later when my services were back). Lucky that a friend emailed me (We don't know what will happened; you are pre-evac, could turn into Evac; come stay in Boulder with us.  Stressful having no heat; had to keep draining water pipes.  Mostly (except for one day) stayed in my cold home; Xcel had to come here many times; finally replaced whole gas meter.  There was ash outside on porch and inside, just inside my doublepane windows.  I was VERY LUCKY that our neighborhood was spared; when I left didn't know what would happen.  Several friends not too far away lost everything.  I am concerned that the high winds will make this a constant problem.  NOTE: ALSO, I have 1.6 acres. Most of it is pasture land grass.  There are fewer and fewer ranchers to cut the hay and feed their animals with that- the custom here for many years.  Do we ALL need to buy our own riding mowers to try to mow all of our land?  Otherwise our whol neighborhood will have lots of long grass just waiting for lightning to start a fire.  Also, nearby are old Xcel power lines that are taking a while (labor shortage, need for poles, etc.) to replace and they keep going down, even in mild breezes.  Those need to be buried.  A fire could result and certainly we are getting more than normal power outages this last month.  Lots of issues here.  Would love for someone who cared to listen to us on these issues in our neighborhood.  If I were younger I might have more energy to organize this myself, but I'm struggling just to manage my own health and property now that I am 79.  MANY THANKS for this survey.  Hope someone reads this!  I am worred about these REAL issues going forward; that affects my state of mind more than just general fear or mental issues.

Or, if there isn't a different version of this for people who lost their homes, you need to rewrite some of those questions!

share_exp: It’s depressing how long it has taken to clean it up.   Driving by and seeing the loss everyday is suffocating.  They should work harder to remove the damage.  Life for the entire town should feel better when all the lots are cleared. Also I fear in 2-3 years there will be so many houses up for sale - that the value of our houses will go down.  I have worked hard all my life and have put a lot into my house

name: Debra & Robert Ervin
share_exp: My heart breaks everytime I go by Old Town Superior  Boulder County is where I was born and raised. This fire, and learning about coal seams all around Colorado that have been burning underground for decades, is quite unsettling to me. I first read abt the Marshall coal seams at the Boulder OEM website, then in the local newspaper, the Boulder Daily Camera.

name: Sarah Elizabeth Martinez & Malcom Dean McGhee
Resident
share_exp: As a renter while the evacuation was still in effect we received an inappropriate message from the rental company asking us to stay inside the rental property to protect the pipes from extreme cold. This was even though the evacuation was still in effect and it was not safe to be there. I rent an older house, after the fire natural gas was turned off and we were out of heat for about a week. It snowed the next couple of days after the fire and it was dangerous to be at home not due to fire/ smoke damage but due to the extreme cold.

name: Jamie & Laura Zukosky
organiz_type: HOA Steele Ranch, Schools (LMS and Monarch)
heal: No but my oldest dog has had a breathing problem since 12/30/2021.
share_exp: Twitter OEM was the only source of information. Luckily we have good neighbors and put together a group text, helping each other get dogs, computers and other things out of houses where people were not home. We had evacuated once before when living in Colorado Springs (Waldo Canyon fire) where our house was saved. This time, I knew exactly what to pack once I saw the smoke and we had our cars filled and ready to go before evacuation orders. Very scary regardless, feel horrible for all the people in our community who lost everything.

name: Resident
share_exp: . I am far enough away from the fire zone that I only experienced extreme high wind with some disruption of outside stored articles and a part of the furnace/hot water vent pipe blown down from the roof that has since been reset.  No loss of roof shingles.   . I cut the grass/weeds in the yard short in the Fall, in preparation for Winter, so if fire had come there would not be much to burn and if even that caught flame I would be outside hosing down the yard near the house and the building itself.  Unlike those structures from Superior to Broomfield there is space between me and neighbors which prevents easy flame hopping from structure to structure.  Being home at the time is a great advantage.    . I wonder if any of those affected, knowing that flames were coming, had tried any self protection strategies ?  In January of 1982 there was a fierce windstorm with somewhat lesser intensity than the Dec. 30, 2021 storm but also caused significant damage, with no fires that I can recall.  A lot of these places that burned on this last one were not even built yet, so a fire back then would have done far less damage had there been one. . Other than the inconvenience of mild ash deposit and the smell of smoke I have no real damage to speak of.

name: John Macrae Huston & Jennifer Shaw Huston

Tracey Pierce
share_exp: I feel the local Louisville government is out of step with the specific needs of this community post fire. It has been too hard of a fight fot families that have lost everything. And to date, of the millions of dollars the community has donated it has been a very slow and confusing process for families to get what they need financially. There was obviously no system in place to distribute funds quickly and ongoingly.  Deadline dates for accessing help are pointless and wrong for people who have been through unprecedented trauma in Boulder County.
